Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas told the UN General Assembly on Thursday that he would sever all agreements with Israel if the country&#39;s future government tries to fulfill Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s promise to annex the occupied Palestinian lands.
&quot;If the future government of Israel that comes into existence proceeds to implement this plan, we will annul all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made,&quot; he announced.
&quot;We will totally and completely reject the whole plan,&quot; Abbas threatened emphatically.
&quot;It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means - no matter what the consequences are - committing ourselves fully to the application of international law and the fight against terrorism,&quot; declared the Palestinian Authority president, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, Israel&#39;s former prime minister, was again tasked with forming a government after the September 17 elections.
A week before the elections, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intended to incorporate all Jewish settlements in the entire West Bank into Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, then led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
Abbas, 84, also promised to hold general elections on Palestinian lands during a session of the UN General Assembly.
The last one took place in 2006.
&quot;When I return to my country, I will call local elections in the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem, and all who oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,&quot; the Palestinian president solemnly declared.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the UN, to exercise the powers vested in &quot;full members of the UN and all its organs and institutions.&quot;
The Palestinian leader concluded his speech by calling on the international community to &quot;force Israel to comply with the provisions of the United Nations with all due respect.&quot;
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas&#39;s speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader &quot;prefers to focus at the UN on the Palestinian Authority&#39;s efforts against Israel, rather than fight calls for terrorism in the PA under his leadership.&quot;
Danon, however, as noted by the agencies, did not refer to Netanyahu&#39;s announced annexation of the occupied Palestinian lands.
