PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Center for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million in funding will go to companies from the gaming industry that create innovative solutions.
On Friday, the National Center for Research and Development announced the results of the third edition of the GameINN program.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the National Center for Research and Development, there are e.g. development of a platform for creating field games based on an AR game engine that creates a map of the real world together with an application that allows users to send data; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills at the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of industry 4.0, according to the NCBR release sent on Friday to PAP.
The aim of the GameINN sectoral program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish sector of video game producers on the global market until 2023.
According to the National Center for Research and Development, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10%. annually.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, and the forecast for 2019 is PLN 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared research agenda of GameINN and the support for entrepreneurs, already reaching PLN 300 million, under this sectoral program are an important impulse for further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedev,” we read in the release.
The video games industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
“The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs who focus on innovation, such as R&amp;D relief, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by the National Center for Research and Development, drive the innovative activity of companies and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market,” assesses the Deputy Prime Minister, Minister Jarosław Gowin, head of science and higher education, quoted in the release.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project co-financing, but also stays in their pockets - in 2018, three quarters more entrepreneurs took advantage of the R&amp;D relief than the year before.
“The amount of deducted costs related to R&amp;D activity amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million in savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the National Center for Research and Development in three editions of GameINN,” emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Director of the National Center for Research and Development, Dr. Eng. Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that in the two previous competitions, co-financing with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million was awarded to 78 innovative projects.
The huge interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of submitted applications show that the video games industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“It is especially pleasing that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects concerning solutions not only for entertainment, but also related to industry 4.0”, he adds.
Entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million in the third GameINN competition.
The NCRD received 87 applications for a total amount of funding of approx. PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in co-financing.
Detailed information on the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sectoral program is implemented as part of the Smart Growth Operational Program.
The NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated in the Polish Games Agreement, which includes, among others, companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
