At the other extreme are the households of pensioners, where the percentage of such answers was only 18%.
The subjective assessment of the financial situation of households is also strongly influenced by the number of children.
Single parents are the worst off, with 32% of them declaring a good or rather good financial situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8 percent.
The effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016), single parents and large families (with at least three children) assessed their financial situation as the worst.
The improvement in the subjective assessment of the financial situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid increase in income, mainly from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good is growing faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The inhabitants of the Opolskie Voivodeship formulate the best opinions, where 48.9% consider their situation to be good or rather good. surveyed.
Then there are Lubuskie (47.7%), Śląskie (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in the Opolskie Voivodeship, the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94 percent the national average, and in Lubuskie 98 percent.
The inhabitants of Mazowiecki (120% of the national average) and Śląskie (104%) had the highest income.
In 2018, the average disposable income per person in Poland was PLN 1,693.
In real terms (adjusted for the impact of price changes), it increased by 4.3%. compared to 2017
This is quite low compared to previous years.
In 2016, income per capita increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3%.
While revenue growth is slowing, expenditure growth is also slowing down.
These per person last year amounted to PLN 1,187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7 percent.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of of their disposable income, while in 2014 this share exceeded 80 percent, and by 2006 it exceeded 90 percent.
