Vote on adjournment for the Conservative Party conference
British MPs have voted against a three-day break in the House of Commons for the Conservative Party&#39;s annual program conference, which was requested by the government.
289 deputies voted for it, 306 against it.
It is customary for the House of Commons not to sit during party conferences, so that MPs do not have to forgo either party conferences or parliamentary sessions.
However, the opposition parties decided that in such a crucial time as the last weeks before the UK&#39;s planned exit from the European Union on October 31, parliament should not interrupt its sessions.
289 deputies were in favor of the government&#39;s request for a break, 306 were against.
Two opposition parties already after the conventions
The lack of consent to the break may be perceived as the opposition&#39;s political revenge on Prime Minister Boris Johnson for his decision to suspend parliament for five weeks (on Tuesday the decision was declared unlawful and null and void by the Supreme Court) and for the fact that, after the judges&#39; ruling, no I want to apologize for her.
Following the ruling, the House of Commons resumed its session on Wednesday, with Johnson&#39;s speech and the heated debate that followed being the highlight of the day.
Johnson accused the opposition of blocking Brexit and avoiding early elections.
“Now is the time to deliver Brexit.
It must be implemented in order to respect the result of the referendum.
Brexit must come so that we can deal with the agreement on citizens&#39; priorities, on health services, on the cost of living.
Brexit must be delivered so that we can unite this country,&quot; Johnson said.
The Conservative Party conference is due to start in Manchester next Sunday and run until Wednesday 2 October.
Conferences of the two main opposition groups - the Labor Party and the Liberal Democrats - have already taken place.
One of Johnson&#39;s reasons for suspending parliament for so long was party conferences.
