Buras worries about Europe
Jáchym Topol has writing in his blood.
Among his ancestors are editors, translators, writers.
Father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important post-war Czech playwrights, today listed in the same row as Václav Havel.
Therefore, Jáchym was cursed with talent from the beginning, which he tries to use.
After eight years, he returned with The Sensitive Man.
The main characters are Buras and Soňa with their two sons, who, however, do not form a typical Czech family.
They are itinerant actors, traveling around Europe.
He is a Shakespeare lover and a thief, she is a one-eyed interpreter who does not part with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys has not made a sound since birth, and for the other, time has stopped in infancy.
But it&#39;s not the characters that are the most important in this story.
All of them are just a background to observe the world in which there is no place for artistic nomads.
It is a world of a flea-infested province, a society of old, suspicious people and dissolute youth.
&quot;The Sensitive Man&quot; sometimes turns into an absurd theater.
The narrative imitates stage directions, and the characters&#39; conversations create this world.
The stage is Europe full of fears about its future, but also constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines canceled 105 flights due to Thomas Cook&#39;s bankruptcy
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook collapsed, its Belgian branch Neckermann is still operational.
However, the company has problems.
Brussels Airlines has announced that it will cancel 105 flights in October due to issues surrounding Thomas Cook&#39;s bankruptcy, VRT has reported.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All tours with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to get a refund.
The court in Ghent also declared bankruptcy of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, approx. 12,000 Belgians stay abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, Thomas Cook Belgium spokeswoman Leen Segers said the company was now &quot;fully operational&quot; despite the UK parent company&#39;s bankruptcy filing, which caused concern among employees and customers.
At that time, the office reassured that customers who bought trips there would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook - the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world - declared bankruptcy on the night from Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse of last-minute talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
Creditors demanded that, in addition to the £900m bailout already agreed in August, the company would raise an extra £200m as collateral for the winter, when travel agents tend to have lower turnover.
However, the company&#39;s problems had been mounting for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6bn.
