Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation per review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion - such an unusual offer has been prepared for newcomers by German Görlitz.
The activities are intended to help fight the progressive decline in the city&#39;s population.
Görlitz is the easternmost city of Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 people a year. tourists.
However, as The Guardian writes, the city is struggling with significant problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a constant decline in the number of inhabitants.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a decrease in the city&#39;s population by 25 percent.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
Wanting to fight depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted for the program.
Two-thirds of them were submitted by residents of large cities.
The program also attracted people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and Great Britain.
“When we applied, we thought the program was to convince people to move to Görlitz,” said one project participant.
&quot;Now we feel it doesn&#39;t matter if we stay here after four weeks or not,&quot; he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
While the city government hopes some will relocate permanently, the main purpose of the program is to solicit feedback from program participants.
Information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
&quot;We want to find out more about what people need and, if they decide to move, what their motivation was,&quot; said program director Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to attract new residents by offering accommodation incentives.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals to live and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the US Tulsa, Oklahoma.
